Peel and slice the @onion{1}(peeled and sliced in half and thinly into half moons). Peel and chop the @carrot{1}(peeled and chopped into ½cm cubes). Lastly, peel and very finely chop the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and finely chopped).

Heat 1 ½ tbsp of @olive oil{1 1/2%tbsp} in a #pot on medium-low heat and add the onion, carrot and garlic. Cook for ~{7%minutes} to soften everything up. You do not want to brown the ingredients, so turn the heat down and add 1 tbsp of @water{1%tbsp} if the heat is too high.

Whilst the mixture gently cooks, peel and chop the @sweet potato{1}(peeled and chopped into 1cm chunks). Slice the @courgette{1} in half lengthways and then slice it into 1cm strips lengthways. Turn it widthways and chop into (roughly) 1cm cubes.

Add the @curry powder mix{2} to the onion and carrot mixture and give it a stir before adding in the sweet potato and the @red split lentils{180%g}. Turn the heat to medium, pour over 600ml of @water{600%ml} and once it comes to a gentle bubble add in the @vegetable stock pot{1}.

Drain and add the @chickpeas{½}(drained), give everything a stir until the stock has dissolved and then leave it to bubble away for ~{15%minutes}.

In the meantime, roughly chop the @coriander{2}(roughly chopped) leaves. 5 mins before the end, tip in the courgette chunks and turn your #oven to 120 degrees. Put your @garlic and coriander naan{1} in the oven and warm it through.

Test the soup for seasoning and add a little more @salt{to taste} if you like. Serve with a sprinkle of fresh coriander, a healthy dollop of @greek style yoghurt{2} and fill your soul!

> If you're anything like our Head Chef Patrick, then you'll appreciate that feeling you have when
> you find a dish you love. And then eat it 5 out of 7 nights a week. That's what happened
> when he whipped up this little number recently. Creature of habit that he is, he made 3 litres
> and ate it with renewed delight every day thereafter. Once you taste its soul-warming
> deliciousness you'll see why.

> You do not want to brown the ingredients when cooking—turn the heat down and add water
> if necessary to keep the mixture from browning.